<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why would an all-powerful God be jealous? That is a human trait.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
from the Hebrew: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>quana</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->: when God is the subject of the verb <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>qana'</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the meaning is 'be zealous', and the preposition <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>le</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (to, for) is used before the object;  His holy name (Eze 39:25) His land (Joel 2:18) and His inheritance (Zec 1:14)  Zec 8:2 &quot;Thus saith the Lord of hosts;  I was jealous for Zion with great jealousy, and I was jealous for her with great fury&quot;<br>
<br>
The verb for 'envy' is nowhere attributed to God in the Old Testament.  So, meanings of the words used in scripture is important to understand.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why does Christianity not accept any other religion? (And in some cases, Protestants do not accept Catholics, and vice versa.) Are Christian beliefs so fragile that they do not hold up when there are other ideas to compare them to? This intolerance and non-acceptance of other religions is one important reason that many of us resist any government attempts to endorse and promote Christianity.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
All religions (even that of unbelief) are exclusive.  There is a difference in 'tolerating' another's beliefs and 'accepting' them as truth.<br>
<br>
I don't think you are looking at the core of the doctrine you believe if you think that other religions are 'tolerant'.  If they are built on a firm foundation, you need to examine it closely; if it appears that the doctrine is accepting of many various ideas and philosophies, there is no foundation.<br>
<br>
