<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why does Christianity not accept any other religion? (And in some cases, Protestants do not accept Catholics, and vice versa.) Are Christian beliefs so fragile that they do not hold up when there are other ideas to compare them to? This intolerance and non-acceptance of other religions is one important reason that many of us resist any government attempts to endorse and promote Christianity.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Jesus said, &quot;I am the way and the truth and the life.  No one comes to the Father except through me.&quot;<br>
<br>
John wrote, &quot;This is how you can recognize the Spirit of God:  Every spirit that acknowledges that Jesus Christ has come in the flesh is from God, but every spirit that does not acknowledge Jesus is not from God.&quot;<br>
<br>
Jesus warned a group of Christians saying, &quot;I know your deeds, that you are neither cold nor hot.  I wish you were either one or the other!  So because you are lukewarm -neither hot nor cold - I am about to spit you out of my mouth.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Bible makes it clear, you are either for Jesus or against Him.  There is no middle ground and to become lukewarm, meaning you're trying to find that middle ground, is worse for you.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Are Christian beliefs so fragile that they do not hold up when there are other ideas to compare them to? This intolerance and non-acceptance of other religions is one important reason that many of us resist any government attempts to endorse and promote Christianity.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
